Here's the registration and the reasoning:

```csharp
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // HttpClient factory — managed pool, avoids socket exhaustion
        builder.Services.AddHttpClient<IDataService, DataService>(client =>
        {
            client.BaseAddress = new Uri("https://api.example.com/");
        });

        // ViewModels — transient so each navigation gets fresh state
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Pages — transient so they pair 1:1 with their ViewModel
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why these lifetimes:**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `DataService` | **Singleton** (via `AddHttpClient`) | Stateless API wrapper. `AddHttpClient` registers it as a typed client with a managed `HttpMessageHandler` pool, avoiding socket exhaustion that a raw `new HttpClient()` per request would cause. One instance is safe and efficient. |
| `ViewModels` | **Transient** | Each navigation should get a clean ViewModel with fresh state. A singleton VM would leak stale data between visits; a scoped VM has no natural scope boundary in MAUI. |
| `Pages` | **Transient** | Mirrors the ViewModel lifetime — each page instance gets its own ViewModel via constructor injection. Avoids stale UI bindings on re-navigation. |

**Key pitfall to avoid:** Don't register `HttpClient` as a singleton directly — the underlying handler won't respect DNS changes. `AddHttpClient<T>` handles handler rotation for you.
